column64:
For anxiety (diagnosed): mindfulness/CBT, exercise, theanine worked best. For ADHD (diagnosed): coping skills/CBT, concerta, mindfulness, exercise, modafinil worked best. 

First, experimented with racetams just out of curiousity about intelligence and whether or not they work (hypothesis: strongly suspected they wouldn't work, given what I have read about IQ, so that may have created an anti-placebo effect for me.) 

Then, fit hit the Shan: I turned to modafinil and various anxiolytics after series of promotions and career successes, starting a family, and buying a home put me in a situation where 1) I was only average compared to my coworkers who (unlike me) have also been at the top of their class in top-tier universities (i.e., had much better time management skills and -- for those with similar conditions -- had developed coping strategies) 2) I could no longer pull all nighters 3) I could no longer "run away" from anxiety by avoiding stressful choices/decisions or outsourcing to others.

Prior to getting professional help (but with some suspicion that I might indeed have had ADHD, some anxiety, and few other conditions), theanine/selank and modafinil helped but in less precise/reliable ways (e.g., sometimes modafinil would help get a project done, but it could also mean I would focus on reading Wikipedia or rewrite the same piece of code over and over, without getting meaningful results; I would use anxiolytics to help me forget about a looming difficulty -- rather than in helping me go through the difficulties in a calm and courageous way). 

As a result of a particularly stressful series of events, I finally sought professional help. Professional therapy (including ruling out several incorrect diagnoses, referral to an MD for prescriptions, CBT, mindfulness practice) was _extremely_ useful in "actuating" the various substances.

One can say that having accesses to various substances is a lot like knowing many programming languages and having access to excellent hardware. Applying CBT, mindfulness, time management skills, and so forth are on the other hand similar to getting a Computer Science education. It's great to be able to write C++ on a 32-core machine with 64gb of RAM; however, these skills/resources are wasted if one uses bubble sort and linear searches instead of quicksort and hash tables.

column64:
Adderall worked great for my adhd but triggered androgenetic alopecia (diagnosed with two biopsy punches, vertical and horizontal) at the age of 22 (I am now 27 and have been off it for 1 year) after 6 months of using it. I am female with no family history of balding. Both of my parents are in their mid 60's with normal hair.  Doctors told me it was unrelated but I do believe it was triggered by it. My hair fell out faster when I was on it. I have since stopped taking it but unfortunately my hair has not recovered as AA is progressive. I suppose I was just unlucky to get this side effect, as it seems to be rare. From my research, those who've lost hair on it were from malnutrition , telogen effluvium or male with history of MPB in their family. I've done alot of on and off with Adderall to help with tolerance and to test what was affecting my hairloss.

 Adderall/stimulants work really well for me except for that. I had no issue / withdrawal symptoms from stopping. I think adderall had triggered some kind of stimulant allergy in me as I've tried ritalin and vyvanse and same side effect of hair coming out. 

I've also used Memantine, Donepzil, tryptophan,modafinil and DMAE  to try and help my ADD but those also accelerate my hair loss.

column64:
TIANEPTINE.  I used to have nightmares as a regular occurrence, something like a 1-in-3 chance upon going to sleep, and usually several nightmares would wake me up in a night where I had any; my count of nightmares was overall slightly higher than my count of nights.  I now take tianeptine before going to bed and that's how it has been life-changing.  I don't have nightmares anymore unless I forget the tianeptine.  As small a dose as 6mg of tianeptine is enough to prevent nightmares most of the time, which is fairy dust; that's approximately one powdered fingertip.  At 15mg, it's reliable.  At 50mg I usually have awesome dreams, but that's edging into euphoriant territory...  I'd do it every night if I weren't afraid of tolerance and habituation effects, but I am, so I usually use the 15mg dose instead.  I'm a vivid dreamer with unusual dream memory, so I can say that other drugs sometimes have characteristic effects on my dreams, but none of those characteristic effects ever stopped the nightmares.  They could change the nightmares, but nothing stopped them until I tried tianeptine.

Also, I clicked the button on phenylpiracetam by accident, and couldn't figure out how to un-click it.  This is a problem for a survey where skipped answers are an important part of the survey's design.  I reviewed my other answers and only the phenylpiracetam answer should be discarded.

column64:
Modafinil gives a feeling of being more "in control", like a big boost to executive function, enabling greater focus. Ideas also subjectively come more readily. I do not think I get to ideas I would not otherwise, but it feels like I get there faster. As a downside, it definitely makes me more irritable, because everyone else just seems slow in comparison. Same story with armodafinil, but armodafinil feels slightly stronger and has somewhat more of a traditional stimulant effect. With caffeine as the baseline 5 for smallest possible real effects, modafinil/armodafinil is a solid 7.

Melatonin I use as a sleep aid, not so much a nootropic. It is very effective at making me sleepier and regulating when I fall asleep. Without it, my body's natural inclination is to be awake until 4AM, but daily use lets me keep a reasonable bed time. As a sleep aid/regulator, it is a 9. As a nootropic, it is a 0, absolutely no effect.

Phenibut is the most powerful substance I have ever used in my life. I am naturally introverted, shy, socially awkward (I have never been diagnosed, but numerous people have accused me of having Asperger's), and have a tendency to social anxiety. Phenibut transforms me into the friendliest person ever and provides a big boost to charisma. It is a life-changer, and is my secret weapon for job interviews. I used to take it regularly, at smaller doses than mentioned above, and cycled off regularly (up to 4 days a week on), but the cycling off process became very unpleasant, so I now only use it when I need the social edge, and would never use it more than once a week. The cycling off unpleasantness consisted of very intense anxiety nightmares, including one that made me wake up literally screaming. In addition, phenibut usage impairs memory creation for me. I credit it with helping me ace my last job interview, but I have very little memory of anything I said. Finally, as a neutral side effect, phenibut will cause me to "hit a wall" the evening of the day I use it, causing me to become very tired and drowsy roughly 3 hours -- 90 minutes before normal bed time. It is totally unsafe to drive in this state, but I have some of the most restful sleep of my life, so it balances out to neutral in my mind. Phenibut is an extremely powerful substance, but it must be treated with the utmost caution. If someone ever develops phenibut without side effects or addictiveness, I will take it regularly. 10 for its positive effects, but a 6 on side effects.

I tried both piracetam and noopept previously, but neither one ever felt like anything more than expensive placebos.

column64:
There are many stimulants that work for the short term but cause massive burnout and rebound effects for me, so I do not use them any longer. I did however, find them appealing in the beginning of my nootropics experimentation and if I may, I would like to caution new nootropic users on this regard. This is what I would write to myself as a starting nootropics user. 

Examples for me are modafinil, yohimbine, and to a lesser extent, ashwagandha. One would have to titrate them very carefully and respect the tolerance accumulation to use them effectively. I do not believe the typical nootropic user is capable of doing this with any regularity, and therefore feel these substances should be used judiciously and only in acute circumstances (maintain wakefulness in cases of extreme need, etc) and not recommended for long term supplementation. In addition, these and similar drugs also cause myself (and I understand many others) to become highly anxious, reflecting a fall off the end of the Yerkes Dodson curve, resulting in hyper-stimulation and increased anxiety that actually impairs performance. 

TL;DR More /= better. Dose response curves are important. Be intelligent with risk.

I am also very easily addicted to caffeine (getting withdrawal headaches severe enough to significantly impede my work), but have not used smart caffeine on consecutive days, so can't speak to addictiveness.

Coffee helped me overcome a food addiction (binge eating disorder) that I'd had for years. I started with a high dose to "addict" myself but now drink just 1-2 cups a day. No side effects, even if I go a day without it. It's been life-changing. I'd managed several binge-free weeks in the past, but mentally, it was always really tough. Since I started drinking coffee, I don't really even think about food outside of mealtimes. Zero mental struggle. Plus, since I started on coffee, I can run faster (even after adjusting for having shed visceral fat) and have more motivation to do things. So I picked up a few new hobbies (piano and jiu jitsu) and have generally become more conscientious and feel incredible. I never realized how much coffee drinkers were cheating at life...

Definite tapering off if I take Modafinil on successive days, four or five is my practical limit.
